Teaching Evaluations and Gender

Is there a difference?

evals <- read.csv("https://www.openintro.org/book/statdata/evals.csv")
aggregate(score ~ gender, FUN = mean, data = evals)
##   gender    score
## 1 female 4.092821
## 2   male 4.234328
t.test(score ~ gender, data = evals)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  score by gender
## t = -2.7507, df = 398.7, p-value = 0.006218
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group female and group male is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.24264375 -0.04037194
## sample estimates:
## mean in group female   mean in group male 
##             4.092821             4.234328

The average evaluation score is 4.09 for female instructors and 4.23 for male instructors, so the male sample average is higher by 0.14 points (on the 15 scale.) A two-tailed Welch \(t\)-test of the hypothesis that both populations have the same mean gives a \(P\)-value of 0.006, meaning theres evidence that the population means of these two groups are in fact different.

Gender and beauty

evalsFemale <- subset(evals, gender == "female")
female.lm <- lm(score ~ bty_avg, data = evalsFemale)
female.lm
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = score ~ bty_avg, data = evalsFemale)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)      bty_avg  
##     3.95006      0.03064
evalsMale <- subset(evals, gender == "male")
male.lm <- lm(score ~ bty_avg, data = evalsMale)
male.lm
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = score ~ bty_avg, data = evalsMale)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)      bty_avg  
##      3.7666       0.1103
plot(evals$bty_avg, evals$score, type = "n", xlab = "Beauty rating", ylab = "Evaluation score", main = "Orange: female instructors; blue: male instructors")
points(evalsFemale$bty_avg, evalsFemale$score, col = "orange")
abline(female.lm, col = "orange")
points(evalsMale$bty_avg, evalsMale$score, col = "blue")
abline(male.lm, col = "blue")

The slope is steeper for male instructors (0.11 to 0.03.) The two regression lines are close together for low beauty ratings, but for higher beauty ratings, male instructors get higher ratings than female instructors on average.

Rust

(a) Create variables and data frame

rust <- read.table("rust.txt", header = TRUE)

# variables from the original dataset
PctWhite <- rust$PctWhite
county <- rust$County

# create new variables according to the instructions
DeathRate <- rust$Deaths / rust$Population * 100000
Density <- rust$Population / rust$Area
logIncome <- log(rust$Income)
Swing <- rust$Trump - (1 - rust$Obama)

# create a new data frame
rust2 <- data.frame(DeathRate, Density, PctWhite, logIncome, Swing, county)

# make a pairs plot
pairs(DeathRate ~ Density + PctWhite + logIncome + Swing, data = rust2)

(b) Interaction model

q1model <- lm(DeathRate ~ Swing + Density + Swing:Density, data = rust2)
q1model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = DeathRate ~ Swing + Density + Swing:Density, data = rust2)
## 
## Coefficients:
##   (Intercept)          Swing        Density  Swing:Density  
##     2.257e+01      1.361e+02      7.068e-03      5.347e-02
AIC(q1model)
## [1] 1372.137
AIC(lm(DeathRate ~ Swing + Density, data = rust2))
## [1] 1373.103

The AIC of the model with an interaction is 1372.1, which is a bit lower than the AIC of the model without the interaction.

Work out equations for Randolph, Monroe, and Marion Counties:

intercepts <- coef(q1model)[1] + coef(q1model)[3] * c(55, 369, 2375)
slopes <- coef(q1model)[2] + coef(q1model)[4] * c(55, 369, 2375)
intercepts
## [1] 22.96331 25.18274 39.36167
slopes
## [1] 139.0838 155.8740 263.1392

This gives the following regression lines: \[ \textrm{Predicted death rate in Randolph-like counties} = 22.96 + 139.1 \times \textrm{Swing} \\ \textrm{Predicted death rate in Monroe-like counties} = 25.18 + 139.1 \times \textrm{Swing}\\ \textrm{Predicted death rate in Marion-like counties} = 39.36 + 263.2 \times \textrm{Swing}\\ \]

A nicer plot than necessary:

library(ggplot2)
rust2$DensityCat <- cut(rust2$Density, breaks = c(10, 100, 1000, 10000))
ggplot(rust2, aes(x = Swing, y = DeathRate, color = DensityCat)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#999999", "#E69F00", "#56B4E9")) +
  geom_abline(intercept = intercepts, slope = slopes, color = c("#999999", "#E69F00", "#56B4E9")) +
  ggtitle("2016 Rust Belt drug deaths as a function of 2016 election swing") +
  xlab("Swing from 2012 to 2016 elections (positive is swing toward Republicans)") +
  ylab("County drug death rate per 100,000 people") +
  labs(color = "Population per square mile", subtitle = c("Regression lines: grey: Randolph County; orange: Monroe County; blue: Marion County"))

In general, counties that swung towards Republicans had higher drug death rates, with bigger effects at high densities. However, the right-hand side of the blue line might be an exaggeration: there are no high-density counties that swung much more than 5 percentage points to Republicans, so we dont know.

(c) Stepwise selection

step(lm(DeathRate ~ 1, data = rust2), scope = formula(max.model), direction = "forward")

step(max.model, direction = "both", trace = 0)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = DeathRate ~ Density + Swing, data = rust2)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)      Density        Swing  
##   2.272e+01    5.408e-03    1.509e+02

All the methods end up converging to the same model:

q2model <- lm(DeathRate ~ Swing + Density, data = rust2)
q2model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = DeathRate ~ Swing + Density, data = rust2)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        Swing      Density  
##   2.272e+01    1.509e+02    5.408e-03

\[ \textrm{DeathRate} = 22.72 + 150.9 \times \textrm{Swing} + 0.005408 \times \textrm{Density} + \textrm{error} \]

AIC(q2model)
## [1] 1373.103

According to the AIC() function, the model has an AIC of 1373.1. (Note that the step() function, which treats constants differently, gives an AIC of 868.8. This is a valid answer here, but isnt comparable to the AIC we calculate in part (b).)
